──── 1C. CANONICAL URLS ───────────────────────────────────

Every page must declare its own canonical URL to prevent
duplicate content penalties if the site is ever scraped
or mirrored.

Update lib/metadata.ts (built in Phase 1):
  Add alternates.canonical to every generatePageMetadata
  call. The canonical URL = siteConfig.url + the page
  path.

Update these pages explicitly:
  app/layout.tsx:
    metadataBase: new URL(siteConfig.url)
    (This is required for Next.js to resolve relative OG
    image URLs to absolute URLs automatically. Add this
    to the root metadata object if not already present.)

  app/page.tsx (homepage):
    alternates: { canonical: siteConfig.url }

  app/projects/page.tsx:
    alternates: { canonical: `${siteConfig.url}/projects` }

  app/blog/page.tsx:
    alternates: { canonical: `${siteConfig.url}/blog` }

  app/projects/[slug]/page.tsx:
    In generateMetadata:
    alternates: {
      canonical: `${siteConfig.url}/projects/${slug}`
    }

  app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx:
    In generateMetadata:
    alternates: {
      canonical: `${siteConfig.url}/blog/${slug}`
    }

──── 1D. JSON-LD STRUCTURED DATA ──────────────────────────

File: components/seo/JsonLd.tsx

JSON-LD is structured data that search engines read to
understand what a page is about. For a portfolio it
enables rich results — Google may show your name, job
title, and social links directly in search results.

This component accepts a `data` prop of type
`Record<string, unknown>` and renders a
<script type="application/ld+json"> tag with the
serialized JSON. Never use dangerouslySetInnerHTML
directly in pages — always use this component.

  export function JsonLd({ data }: {
    data: Record<string, unknown>
  }) {
    return (
      <script
        type="application/ld+json"
        dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{
          __html: JSON.stringify(data)
        }}
      />
    )
  }

