──── 3A. BUNDLE ANALYSIS ──────────────────────────────────

Install: @next/bundle-analyzer

Update next.config.ts:

  import bundleAnalyzer from '@next/bundle-analyzer'

  const withBundleAnalyzer = bundleAnalyzer({
    enabled: process.env.ANALYZE === 'true',
  })

  export default withBundleAnalyzer({
    // existing config
  })

Add to package.json scripts:
  "analyze": "ANALYZE=true pnpm build"

Run: pnpm analyze

Open the generated .next/analyze/client.html in browser.

Look for and fix these common issues:

  ISSUE 1 — Large library imported in full:
    Symptom: lodash, date-fns, or any utility library
    showing as 50KB+ in client bundle.
    Fix: use named imports or find a lighter alternative.
    Example: import { format } from 'date-fns' not
             import dateFns from 'date-fns'

  ISSUE 2 — Framer Motion in the wrong bundle:
    Symptom: framer-motion appearing in initial page load
    bundle instead of being lazy loaded.
    Fix: verify all Framer Motion usage is in 'use client'
    components and those components are not imported in
    RSC pages without dynamic() wrapping.

  ISSUE 3 — highlight.js full library imported:
    Symptom: highlight.js showing 200KB+ in bundle.
    Fix: import only needed languages:
      import hljs from 'highlight.js/lib/core'
      import javascript from 'highlight.js/lib/languages/javascript'
      import typescript from 'highlight.js/lib/languages/typescript'
      hljs.registerLanguage('javascript', javascript)
      hljs.registerLanguage('typescript', typescript)
    Add: bash, css, json as well (common in blog posts).

  ISSUE 4 — Lucide React importing all icons:
    Symptom: lucide-react showing as 500KB+
    Fix: verify every import is named:
      import { ArrowRight } from 'lucide-react'
    Never: import * as Icons from 'lucide-react'
    Search entire codebase for 'import * from lucide' and
    fix any violations.

  ISSUE 5 — next-mdx-remote in client bundle:
    Symptom: mdx-remote appearing in client-side JS.
    Fix: ensure MDXRemote is only used in RSC files
    (no 'use client' at top of files using MDXRemote).

After fixes: re-run pnpm analyze and verify each issue
is resolved before moving on.

──── 3B. IMAGE AUDIT ──────────────────────────────────────

Run this audit across every image in the project:

  RULE 1 — No raw <img> tags anywhere.
    Search: grep -r "<img " app/ components/
    Every result must be converted to next/image.

  RULE 2 — Every next/image has explicit sizes prop.
    Without sizes, Next.js serves a full-width image
    even for thumbnail-sized usage.
    Examples:
      Full width hero:   sizes="100vw"
      Half width:        sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw,
                                50vw"
      Project card:      sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw,
                                (max-width: 1024px) 50vw,
                                33vw"
      Fixed thumbnail:   sizes="192px"

  RULE 3 — priority={true} on above-the-fold images only.
    Above fold: hero image, hero code card illustration,
    first visible project card image.
    All others: default (lazy loaded).
    Using priority on too many images defeats the purpose.

  RULE 4 — All project and blog images under 200KB.
    Check /public/images/ file sizes.
    If any PNG is over 200KB: convert to WebP.
    Next.js serves WebP automatically when the browser
    supports it, but starting with WebP reduces the
    original file size too.
    Tool: squoosh.app (browser-based, free)
    Target: project covers ~100KB, blog covers ~80KB.

  RULE 5 — OG images are generated, not static files.
    /public/og-image.png (the placeholder from Phase 1)
    is no longer needed — remove it.
    The dynamic opengraph-image.tsx files now handle this.

